In Java, catch blocks must be ordered from specific → general

But in this code:
catch (Exception e)   //General exception
catch (ArithmeticException ex)  //Specific exception

Exception is the parent class
ArithmeticException is the child class

So the first catch block:
catch (Exception e)
will already catch ALL exceptions, including ArithmeticException.

That makes the second catch block unreachable
Compile-Time Error

Java will give error like:
Unreachable catch block for ArithmeticException


Correct Code
try {
    int a = 10 / 0;
} catch (ArithmeticException ex) {
    System.out.println("Can't divide by zero " + ex);
} catch (Exception e) {
    System.out.println("General exception " + e);
}
Output
Can't divide by zero java.lang.ArithmeticException: / by zero

Not accomplished because the general exception (Exception) is placed before the specific exception (ArithmeticException), making the later catch block unreachable.